"L E S S O N Distributive Property Order of Operations Power Up Building Power facts Power Up E mental math a. Calculation: Damian rides his bike 10 miles per hour for 21 2 hours. How far does he ride? b. Estimation: $3.49 + $1.49 + $6.49 + $3.49 c. Algebra: 34 − x = 25 d. Power/Roots: 2144 e. Number Sense: 16 × 5 f. Fractional Parts: Three fourths of a dollar is how many cents? g. Calculation: 12 × 3, 2 , × 7, − 2, ÷ 5, + 1, 2 , ÷ 2 problem solving Cameron and Ann are the two finalists in a chess tournament. The first player to win either two consecutive games, or a total of three games, wins the match and the tournament. How many different ways can their match be played out? Understand Two players are in a chess tournament, and the winner of the match will be the player who either wins two games in a row, or is the first player to win a total of three games. Plan We will make a table of the possible outcomes of the match. We will include in our list the number of games it is necessary to play, who won each game, and who the won the match. Solve # of Games Played Who Won Each Game Match Winner 2 games CC Cameron AA Ann 3 games CAA Ann ACC Cameron 4 games CACC Cameron ACAA Ann 5 games CACAC Cameron ACACA Ann CACAA Ann ACACC Cameron"
"Saxon Math Course 3 Check Tournaments are a part of almost any competitive activity, and you may be familiar with other formats for determining a winner. Our organized list shows that there are ten different ways the chess match can be played out. New Concepts Increasing Knowledge distributive property These two formulas can be used to find the perimeter of a rectangle. 1. P = 2( l + w) 2. P = 2l + 2w Using the first formula we add the length and width (12 cm + 8 cm = 20 cm). Then we double this sum (2 × 20 cm = 40 cm). Using the second formula we double the length (2 × 12 cm = 24 cm) and double the width (2 × 8 cm = 16 cm). Then we add these products (24 cm + 16 cm = 40 cm). Both formulas produce the same result because the formulas are equivalent. 2( l + w) = 2l + 2w These two formulas illustrate the Distributive Property (sometimes called the Distributive Property of Multiplication over Addition). The Distributive Property gives us a choice when dealing with expressions such as this one. 2(12 + 8) One choice is to add before multiplying, 2(20). The other choice is to multiply each addend before adding. 2(12  8)  2 ∙ 12  2 ∙ 8 The second choice distributes the multiplication over the addition. Here we show in symbols the Distributive Property over addition and subtraction. Distributive Property a( b + c) = a ∙ b + a ∙ c a(b + c + d ) = a ∙ b + a ∙ c + a ∙ d a(b − c) = a ∙ b − a ∙ c The Distributive Property works in two ways. We can expand and we can factor. • We expand 2(a + b) and get 2a + 2b. • We factor 2a + 2b and get 2(a + b). Notice that we used the word factor as a verb. We factor an expression by writing the expression as a product of two or more numbers or expressions. Explain How can we factor the expression 15 + 10? Explain and rewrite the expression. 12 cm 8 cm"
"Example 1 a. Expand: 3(w + m) b. Factor: ax + ay Solution a. To expand, we distribute the multiplication 3(w + m). 3(w + m) = 3w + 3m b. To factor, we divide both terms by a. ax + ay = a(x + y) Example 2 a. Expand: 3(x + 2) b. Factor: 6x + 9 Solution a. We multiply each term within the parentheses by 3. 3(x + 2) = 3x + 6 b. We see that 3 is a factor of both terms. We remove by division a factor of 3 from each term. 6x + 9 = 3(2x + 3) When factoring, we may prefer to write each term as a product of factors before applying the distributive property. 6x + 9 Given expression 2 ∙ 3 ∙ x + 3 ∙ 3 Factored each term 3(2x + 3) Factored 3 from each term order of operations If there is more than one operation in an expression, we follow this order. 1. Simplify within parentheses. 2. Simplify exponent expressions. 3. Multiply and divide in order from left to right. 4. Add and subtract in order from left to right. The first letters of the boldfaced words are also the first letters of the words in the following sentence, which can help us remember this order. Please excuse my dear Aunt Sally. If there are operations within the parentheses we follow the order of operations to simplify within the parentheses."
"Saxon Math Course 3 Example 3 Simplify: 20 − 2 ∙ 32 + (7 + 8) ÷ 5 Solution Step: Justification: 20 − 2 ∙ 32 + 15 ÷ 5 Simplified within parentheses 20 − 2 ∙ 9 + 15 ÷ 5 Applied exponent 20 − 18 + 3 Multiplied and divided Added and subtracted Brackets [ ] and braces { } are used as grouping symbols like parentheses. We use brackets to enclose parentheses and braces to enclose brackets. 10 − {8 − [6 − (5 − 3)]} To simplify expressions with multiple grouping symbols, we begin from the inner most symbols. Example 4 Simplify: 10 − {8 − [6 − (5 − 3)]} Solution We simplify within the parentheses, then the brackets, then the braces. Step: Justification: 10 − {8 − [6 − (5 − 3)]} Given expression 10 − {8 − [6 − 2]} Simplified in parentheses 10 − {8 − 4} Simplified in brackets 10 − 4 Simplified in braces Subtracted Absolute value symbols, division bars, and radicals sometimes group multiple terms as well. Example 5 Simplify: a. |2 − 7| b. 29  16 12  12 3  3 Solution We simplify within the absolute value symbols. |2 − 7| = |−5| = We simplify under the radical. 29  16  225 ="
"c. We simplify above and below the division bar first. 12  12 3  3  144 6 = 24 Example 6 Consider this expression: 3 + 3 × 3 − 3 ÷ 3 a. As written, this expression equals what number? b. Copy the expression and place one pair of parentheses so that the expression equals 3. Justify your answer. Solution a. 11 b. 3 + 3 × (3 − 3) ÷ 3 3 + 3 × 0 ÷ 3 Simplified within parentheses 3 + 0 Multiplied and divided left to right Added Practice Set Perform the indicated multiplication. a. 2(3 + w) b. 5(x − 3) Factor each expression. c. 9x + 6 d. 8w − 10 e. Analyze Which property is illustrated by the following equation? x( y + z) = xy + xz f. Explain Why might you use the Distributive Property to simplify 3(30 − 2)? Simplify. g. 2 + 5 ∙ 2 − 1 h. (2 + 5) ∙ (2 − 1) i. 4 + (11 − 32) ∙ 23 j. 10 − [8 − (6 − 3)] k. 236  64 l. |8 − 12| m. The expression 22 + 2 × 2 − 2 ÷ 2 equals 7. Copy the expression and insert one pair of parentheses to make the expression equal 11."
"Saxon Math Course 3 Written Practice Strengthening Concepts * 1. (3) Bob drove from his home near Los Angeles to his destination in Sacramento in 7 hours. The next time he made his trip, he flew. He drove 1 2 hour to the airport, spent 11 2 hours at the airport, had a 1 hour flight, and arrived at his destination 1 hour after landing. Considering Bob’s total travel time, how much time did it save Bob to fly rather than drive? 2. (3, 4) George chopped 8 times in the first 30 seconds. Then he chopped 5 times in the next 20 seconds. Finally he chopped 2 times in the last 10 seconds. How many times did he chop? How long did it take him? When was he chopping the most rapidly? 3. (7) John read 66 books in one year. At this rate, how many would he read in four months? * 4. (2) a. How can these numbers be rearranged to make the addition easier? 7 + (18 + 13) b. What two properties did you use? c. What is the sum? 5. (2) Use the Associative and Commutative Properties of Multiplication to find the product of these numbers mentally. 12 ∙ 13 ∙ 5 ∙ 10 Write the order in which you multiplied the numbers. What is the product? * 6. (21) Formulate Linda reserved two hotel rooms for $75 each room plus a tax of $7.50 each. Illustrate the Distributive Property by writing two ways to compute the total. What is the total? 7. (8, 17) Estimate the area of this figure. * 8. (21) a. Expand: 2(x + 7) b. Factor: 9x + 12 * 9. (20) Classify this triangle by sides and by angles and state the measure of each angle. C B A 6.3 cm 41 cm"
"10. (7) The numbers of students playing soccer after school Monday through Friday were 20, 22, 19, 25, and 24. What was the mean number of students playing soccer that week? Generalize Simplify. * 11. (21) 1 + 2 + 3 × 4 + 5 * 12. (10, 21) 2  5 1  20 13. (13) 21 − 2 14. (13) 13 5  1 1 15. (2) * 16. (15) * 17. (15) 3 27 * 18. (15) 34 19. (Inv. 1, 8) Plot the following points, connect the points to make a rectangle, and find the area and perimeter of the rectangle. (−5, 7), (3, 7), (3, −2), (−5, −2) * 20. (1, 21) Analyze Compare. 20 − 33 |20 − 33| 21. (1) Find the two values for r which make this statement true: | r | = 2. * 22. (15) Write in exponential form: bbrr yyyy * 23. (20, Inv. 2) Find the perimeter and area of this triangle. 6 cm 8 cm For problems 24−27, solve by inspection. 24. (14) 27 + w = 35 25. (14) y  2 26. (14) 8n + 2 = 90 27. (14) 2b − 3 = 5 * 28. (14, 15) Evaluate Find b2 − 4ac when a = 2, b = 3, c = 1 29. (6, 8) How many square yards of carpet are needed to cover the floor of a classroom that is 30 ft long and 30 ft wide? * 30. (10, 16) Name four sets of numbers of which zero is a member."
"L E S S O N Saxon Math Course 3 Multiplying and Dividing Fractions Power Up Building Power facts Power Up E mental math a. Calculation: Madrid read 20 pages per hour. How many pages can she read in 1 1 4 hours? b. Geometry: When we write a congruence statement for a polygon, we write the corresponding vertices in the same order for both polygons. Copy and complete this statement: △ ABC ≅ △ X_ _ A C B X R w c. Number Sense: 14 ÷ 4 d. Fractional Parts: 1 4 of 120 e. Proportions: If four of the boxes weigh 20 pounds, how much would six of the boxes weigh? f. Power/Roots: 216  216 g. Percent: 25% of 400 h. Calculation: 1000 ÷ 2, ÷ 2, ÷ 2, − 25, ÷ 2, ÷ 2, − 25, ÷ 2, − 25 problem solving These two congruent squares of note paper can be overlapped to form polygons with as few as 4 sides or as many as 16 sides. Are there polygons with other numbers of sides that can be formed by overlapping congruent squares? Understand We know that a polygon is a closed shape. The polygons given in the problem are both concave, because it is possible to connect two points located inside the polygon with a segment that goes outside the polygon. Plan This is a good problem to solve by using a model and acting it out, so we will need to locate or create two congruent squares."
"Solve We will leave one of our squares stationary, and rotate and slide the second square: 7 sides 8 sides 9 sides 13 sides Look Back We have constructed polygons with 7, 8, 9, and 13 sides by sliding the two squares. We may be able to form different polygons with other numbers of sides. A natural extension of this problem would be to work with a variety of shapes, such as two congruent rectangles, or a square and a rectangle New Concept Increasing Knowledge Pictured below are containers for a gallon, a quart, and a pint. We can use these measures to illustrate the multiplication of fractions. A quart is 1 4 of a gallon, and a pint is 1 2 of a quart. What fraction of a gallon is a pint? 1 pint 1 quart 1 gallon Milk A pint is 1 2 of 1 4 of a gallon. By multiplying 1 2 and 1 4, we find that a pint is 1 8 of a gallon. 2  1 4  1 Notice that the numerator of 1 8 is the product of the numerators, and the denominator is the product of the denominators. Also notice that 1 8 is less than both factors. An area model can also help us visualize the result of multiplying fractions. Here we show a 1 inch- by-1 inch square. Within the square is a small, shaded square that is 1 2 inch-by-1 2 inch. Notice the shaded square is 1 4 the area of the larger square. This model illustrates the multiplication of 1 2 and 1 2. 2  1 2  1 To multiply fractions we multiply the numerators to find the numerator of the product, and we multiply the denominators to find the denominator of the product. Example 1 Multiply 1 3 and 2 3. Use an area model to illustrate the multiplication. 1 in. 1 in. in. in."
"Saxon Math Course 3 Solution Multiply the numerators. Multiply the denominators 3  2 3  2 We draw a square and divide two adjacent sides into thirds, extending the divisions across the square. Then we shade an area with sides 1 3 and 3 long. We see that 2 9 of the square is shaded. Example 2 What number is 3 4 of 8 9? Solution To find 3 4 of 8 9 we multiply the fractions. We may reduce before we multiply (cancel).  8  2 Discuss Why might we want to reduce before we multiply? If the product of two fractions is 1, the fractions are reciprocals. 3  3 f  6 6  1 reciprocals We can form the reciprocal of a fraction by reversing the numbers of the numerator and denominator of the fraction. Some say we invert a fraction to form its reciprocal. This expression comes from another name for reciprocal, multiplicative inverse. Example 3 a. What is the reciprocal of 5 6? b. What is the multiplicative inverse of 3? c. How many 1 4s are in 1? d. How many 2 3s are in 1? Solution a. The reciprocal of 5 6 is 6 5. b. The multiplicative inverse of 3 (or 3 1 ) is 1 3."
"c. The number of 1 4s in 1 is 4 (or 4 1 ), which is the reciprocal of 1 4. d. The number of 2 3s in 1 is the reciprocal of 2 3, which is 3 2. We use reciprocals to help us divide fractions. If we want to know the number of 3 4s in 2, we divide 2 by 3 4. 2  3 We perform the division in two steps. First we find the number of 3 4s in 1, which is the reciprocal of 3 4. 1  3 4  4 There are twice as many 3 4s in 2 as there are in 1, so we multiply 4 3 by 2. 2  4 3  8 3  22 We can combine the two steps and multiply by the reciprocal of the divisor. 2  3 2  4 3  8 3  22 Example 4 A quart is 1 4 of a gallon. A pint is 1 8 of a gallon. How many 1 8s are in 1 4? Solution Thinking Skill Connect There are 2 cups in a pint. How many cups are in a gallon? What fraction of a gallon is one cup? How are the two numbers related? The question “How many are in. . .?” is a division question. We divide 1 4 by 1 8. 4  1 4  8 1  8 4  2 The answer is reasonable. Two 1 8s equal 1 4, and two pints equal a quart. Example 5 Simplify: 3 4  1 Solution We show two methods. First method: Find the number of 1 3s in 1. 1  1 3  3 Then find 3 4 of this number. 4  3  9 4  21"
"Saxon Math Course 3 Second method: Rewrite the division problem as a multiplication problem and multiply by the reciprocal of the divisor. 4  1 4  3 1  9 4  21 Practice Set a. Model Multiply 1 4 and 1 2. Use an area model to illustrate the multiplication. b. One half of the students in the class are boys. One third of the boys walk to school. Boys who walk to school are what fraction of the students in the class? Generalize Simplify. c. 1 2  3 d. 5 6  2 e. What number is 1 2 of 3 4? f. What number is 2 3 of 3 4? For g and h write the multiplicative inverse (reciprocal) of the number. g. 3 h. 4 i. How many 2 3 s are in 1? j. 1  3 k. 1  1 l. How many 1 2 s are in 3 4 ? (3 4  1 2) Simplify. m. 2 3  3 n. 3 4  2 Written Practice Strengthening Concepts 1. (7) Mariya ran 14 miles in one week. At that rate, how many miles would she run in 5 days? * 2. (3, 7) Analyze The triathlete swam 2 miles in 56 minutes. Then, he rode his bicycle 100 miles in 5 hours. Finally, he ran 20 miles in 160 minutes. How many minutes did it take him to complete the course? During which portion of the race did he have the greatest average speed? * 3. (21) Expand: 3(x + 7) * 4. (21) Factor: 5x + 35 * 5. (21) 6  4 7  2 * 6. (21) 6 + 5 × 4 − 3 + 2 ÷ 1 * 7. (1, 21) Compare: |6 − 19| (6 − 19) * 8. (22) 4  1"
"* 9. (22) What number is 1 3 of 3 5 ? * 10. (22) Generalize What is the reciprocal of 1 7 ? * 11. (22) What is the multiplicative inverse of 2 3 ? 12. (14) Find x2 + 2yz when x = 4, y = 5, and z = 7. * 13. (22) 4  1 * 14. (8, 20) Generalize Find the perimeter and area of this triangle. * 15. (20) Classify Classify this triangle by angles and sides, and state the measure of each angle. 16. (8) Find the area of a square with a side length of 17 in. 17. (19) Explain Is this figure a polygon? Explain why or why not. 18. (20) Can an obtuse triangle be regular? Explain why or why not. 19. (19) Choose the appropriate symbol to complete this statement: △ EFG △ XYZ G F E Z Y X A ≅ B ∼ C = D < 20. (18) ∠WYX and ∠ XYZ form a linear pair. If m∠ XYZ is 60º, find m∠ WYX. 21. (18) Name this figure A EF ¡ B FE ¡ C either A or B 13 cm 12 cm 5 cm E F"
"Saxon Math Course 3 22. (18) A freeway passes under a street. If we think of the freeway and the street as lines, we would say the lines are: A intersecting B parallel C skew 23. (17) Round $403,500,000 to the nearest million. 24. (17) Estimate the product (17.89)(97 8). 25. (1) Name a set of numbers that includes 1, but not zero. 26. (15) 2 3 64 27. (13) 11 3 + 11 28. (12 Write 7 8 as a decimal number. 29. (5) What is 3 5 of 35? * 30. (20) Generalize A home in the mountains is going to be built with a steep roof to keep heavy snow from accumulating on the roof. If the roof is at a 70º angle as shown, what is the angle at the peak? 70° °"
"L E S S O N Multiplying and Dividing Mixed Numbers Power Up Building Power facts Power Up E mental math a. Calculation: Robbie ran ten miles per hour. How many minutes would it take Robbie to run 2 miles? b. Geometry: Two angles of a triangle are 90º and 35º. What is the measure of the third angle? c. Number Sense: $18 ÷ 4 d. Proportions: If 2 pounds cost $5, how much would 3 pounds cost? e. Percent: 25% of 104 f. Algebra: 54 x = 0.54 g. Fractional Parts: 1 3 of 93 h. Calculation: 7 + 3, × 10, ÷ 2, ÷ 10, + 2, × 9, + 1, 2 , + 1, 2 , + 1, 2 , − 1, 2 , − 1 problem solving We can use tree diagrams to help us identify possible combinations or possible outcomes of probability experiments. Problem: The security guard can choose from three different shirts and two different pairs of pants for his uniform. How many different combinations does he have to choose from? Understand We are told that the guard has three different shirts and two different pants. We are asked to find the numbers of different uniform combinations he has to choose from. Plan We will make a tree diagram to show the possible combinations. We will use the first set of branches for the three shirts ( A , B , C ) and the second set of branches for pants (1, 2). Solve Combination Tree Shirt-Pants Combinations Pants 1 A 1 A 2 B 1 B 2 C 1 C 2 Pants 2 Pants 1 Pants 2 Pants 1 Pants 2 Shirt A Shirt B Shirt C We identify 6 different possible combinations."
Saxon Math Course 3 Check We look back at the problem with our solution in mind to be sure we have answered the question and that our answer is reasonable. We were asked for the number of combinations of shirts and pants. We answered 6. Our answer is reasonable because for each choice of shirt there are two choices of pants. New Concept Increasing Knowledge Thinking Skill Explain How do we write whole numbers as improper fractions? To multiply or divide mixed numbers we first write each mixed number (or whole number) as a fraction. A mixed number can be converted into a fraction as we illustrate. 4  4 4  4 4  1 4  9 Another way to perform the conversion is to multiply the whole number by the denominator and add the numerator to find the numerator of the new fraction. 4 × 2 + 1 = 9  2 1 If the answer is an improper fraction we might choose to convert the improper fraction to a mixed number. We do so by dividing the numerator by the denominator. 4 =  8 4 9 = 21 The remainder becomes the numerator of the fraction part of the mixed number. Example 1 Simplify: a. 21 3  11 b. 12 3  21 Solution a. First we rewrite each mixed number as an improper fraction. Then we multiply. 3  11 3  3 2  21 6  33 6  31 The product is an improper fraction which we can convert to a mixed number. We reduce the fraction. Visit www. SaxonPublishers. com/ActivitiesC3 for a graphing calculator activity.
"b. We write the mixed numbers as improper fractions. Instead of dividing, we multiply by the reciprocal of the divisor. 3  21 3  5 3  2 5  10 15  2 a and b could be reduced before multiplying. We may reduce (or cancel) to eliminate the need to reduce after multiplying. a. 7  3 2  7 2  31 b. 5 3  2  2 Example 2 A carpenter is nailing horizontal boards to the outside surface of a building. The exposed portion of each board is 63 4 in. How many rows of boards are needed to reach to the top of an 8 ft wall? Solution We begin by converting 8 ft to 96 in. Then we divide 96 in. by 63 4 in. 96  63 1  27 1  4  128  142 Fourteen boards is not enough. To reach to the top of the wall the carpenter will need 15 rows of boards. 8 ft in. 6 3"
"Saxon Math Course 3 The following table shows the steps we take to multiply and divide fractions and mixed numbers. Multiplying and Dividing Fractions and Mixed Numbers 1. Write whole numbers or mixed numbers as fractions. 2. Multiplying Dividing Multiply numerators. Instead of dividing, multiply by Multiply denominators. the reciprocal of the divisor. 3. Simplify the answer by reducing if possible. Improper fractions may be expressed as whole or mixed numbers. Practice Set a. What is the area of a rectangle 21 inches long and 11 inches wide? b. A recipe calls for 13 cups of milk. How many cups of milk are needed if the recipe is doubled? c. A tile setter is covering a 5 ft by 5 ft square shower wall. Each tile covers a 45 8 in. by 8 in. square. How many rows of tile are needed to reach 5 feet? How many tiles are needed to cover the 5 ft by 5 ft square? Write the multiplicative inverse (reciprocal) of each number. d. 22 e. 5 f. 5 Simplify. g. 11 2  12 h. 21 2  21 i. 11 2  22 j. 22 3  11 Written Practice Strengthening Concepts 1. (3) Analyze At the wedding the guests sat on either side of the banquet hall. There were 109 guests seated on the left side. If there were 217 guests in all, how many sat on the right side of the aisle? 2. (5) Visitors to the school’s website can follow a link to the school’s chorale pictures. If the website had 250 visitors in one week and 3 10 of them visited the chorale pictures, how many visited the chorale pictures? 3. (3) Martin Luther was born in 1483, which was twenty-seven years after the invention of the printing press. In what year was the printing press invented? * 4. (13) 6  1 * 5. (13) 6  1 * 6. (22) 6  1 * 7. (22) 6  1 5 ft 5 ft"
