"L E S S O N Saxon Math Course 3 Laws of Exponents Power Up Building Power facts Power Up F mental math a. Calculation: Roper does 20 pushups per minute. If he can do 50 pushups at this rate, how long will it take? b. Number Sense: 21 2  12 c. Geometry: Find x. d. Algebra: 4x − 3 = 25 e. Fractional Parts: 2 5 of $55 f. Proportions: Walking up 3 stair steps, Vera rose 2 feet. How many feet did Vera rise walking up 12 stair steps? g. Percent: 25% of 444 h. Calculation: 2100, − 1, 2 , × 12, 2 , × 4, + 1, 2 , × 10, − 1, 2 problem solving Sharon took Susan to a playground. Use the graph to write a brief story about what Susan was doing on the playground. Time In Minutes Height From Ground In Feet Susan’s Trip to the Playground Understand We have been given a graph that shows how many feet Susan was above the ground over a span of 17 minutes of play on a playground. We are asked to write a brief story of what she was doing while on the playground. Plan The motion graph that we have been provided shows three distinct events in terms of height. The first event shows a gradual rise up, and then a sudden drop down. The second event shows a consistent up-and-down. The third event shows an extended amount of time at approximately 4 feet. Solve Susan arrived at the play area and immediately ran to the slide. She waited her turn to climb up the rungs to the top, where she hesitated for a while before finally sliding down. She then walked over to the swings where she began to swing, gradually gaining altitude, and then slowing down so she could get off. Finally, Susan decided to play in the “Tubes and Tunnels.” She climbed up the steps, and then spent several minutes crawling through the tunnels before exiting down the stairs. Check We were able to write a story because Susan’s movement on the playground had been graphed. Other stories may differ from ours. x∘ x∘ 80∘"
"New Concept Increasing Knowledge Recall that a counting-number exponent indicates how many times a base is a factor. Math Language The exponent, or n, shows the number of times the base, or x, is used as a factor. xn = x ∙ x ∙ x . . . x (n factors of x) Applying this knowledge we can begin to develop the laws of exponents that describe relationships between exponents for certain operations. Example 1 Find the missing exponent: x 5 ∙ x 3 = x Solution We apply the meaning of the exponents. x5 ∙ x3 = (x ∙ x ∙ x ∙ x ∙ x)(x ∙ x ∙ x) = x We see that multiplying x5 and x3 means that x is a factor eight times. Notice that the exponent 8 is the sum of the exponents 5 and 3. Example 2 Find the missing exponent: 35 33  3 Solution We apply the meaning of the exponents and reduce the fraction. 33  3  3  3  3  3 1  3 1  3 = 3 Notice that the exponent 2 is the difference of the exponents 5 and 3. Example 3 Find the missing exponent: (x3)2 = x Solution The exponent 2 means that the base x 3 is a factor twice. (x3)2 = x3 ∙ x3 = xxx ∙ xxx = x Notice that the exponent 6 is the product of the exponents 2 and 3."
"Saxon Math Course 3 Thinking Skill Connect Why does the table specify that for division, x ≠ 0? Examples 1, 2, and 3 illustrate the following three laws of exponents. xa ∙ xb = xa+b xa xb  xab for x ≠ 0 (xa)b = xa∙b Laws of Exponents for Multiplication and Division Summarize State the laws of exponents as shown in the table in your own words. We will expand on these laws in later lessons. Example 4 Write each expression as a power of ten. a. 108 ∙ 106 b. 108 Solution The bases are the same, so we can apply the laws of exponents. a. We add the exponents. 108 ∙ 106 = 1014 b. We subtract the exponent of the divisor from the exponent of the dividend. 106  102 Practice Set Find the missing exponents. a. x 5 ∙ x 2 = x b. x5 x2  x c. (x2)3 = x Simplify. d. 23 ∙ 22 e. 25 f. (25)2 Write each expression as a power of 10. g. 106 ∙ 103 h. 106 Written Practice Strengthening Concepts 1. (7) Cynthia planted 12 potted plants in the last 3 weeks. At that rate, how many would she plant in 5 weeks? 2. (5) The volleyball team has 5 wins and 7 losses. What fraction of their games will they have won if they win their next 3 games? 3. (5) Of the 2,800 visitors to the fair, only 3 70 won a prize. How many visitors won prizes?"
