"Saxon Math Course 3 Triangles, however, are stable. So engineers require triangles in buildings to increase the stability of the building. Just one diagonal brace greatly increases the stability of a wall. Conrad will use a board to brace the wall of a shed as shown. Is a 10-foot long board long enough? Justify your answer. Generalize Simplify: * 14. (31, 51) (−1)2 + (−1)1 + (−1)0 + (−1)−1 15. (27) race car  e 16. (13, 22) a2 3b  1 3  3 17. (31, 36) x(x + 2) − 2 (x + 2) Analyze Solve. * 18. (50) 1.3x − 0.32 = 0.98 * 19. (50) 0.001x + 0.09 = 1.1 * 20. (50) −4(2 + x) − 2(x + 3) = 4 21. (38) 7x  3 22. (56) Using slope-intercept form, write the equation of each line. Graph each solution on a number line. * 23. (62) x + 2 < 6 * 24. (62) x + 5 ≥ 3 25. (Inv. 5) a. Square ABCD has these vertices: A(−2, 2), B(2, 2), C(2, −2) and D(−2, −2). Use graph paper to draw square ABCD and similar figure A′B′C′D′ using a scale factor of 4. (Assume that the origin is the center of both figures.) b. What are the locations of the vertices of A′B′C′D′? x a b y 96 in. 64 in."
"L E S S O N Rational Numbers, Non-Terminating Decimals, and Percents Fractions with Negative Exponents Power Up Building Power facts Power Up M mental math a. Percent: 30% of $80 b. Statistics: Find the mean of these numbers: 20, 40, 50, 30, 10 c. Sequences: Find the next three terms. 1, 2, 4, 8, , , , . . . d. Fractional Parts: 1 9 of 7200 e. Measurement: The odometer read 438.1 miles before the trip. Now it reads 449.9 miles. How long was the trip? f. Proportion: 2 3  8 x g. Scientific Notation: (2.0 × 105)(3.0 × 106) h. Calculation: Square 10,  1,  11, 2 , × 5,  1, 2 , 2 problem solving Greg rode his bike up the 30 mile hill at 10 miles per hour. Then, he rode back down the hill at 30 miles per hour. How far did he go altogether? How long did it take him? What was his average speed? New Concepts Increasing Knowledge rational numbers, non- terminating decimals, and percents Recall that every rational number can be expressed as a ratio of two integers. Converting the ratio to a decimal number results in a decimal that terminates (ends) or does not terminate but has repeating digits. Terminating: 8 = 0.125 Reading Math Recall that the three dots (. . .) is called an ellipsis. It indicates that the pattern of repetition continues. An ellipsis may be used in place of a bar. Non-terminating but repeating: 11 = 0.0909090909. . . Also recall that we can indicate repeating digits by writing a bar over the repetend. 11  0.09 We do not perform computations with a decimal number that has a bar over the repetend. Instead we use the fraction equivalent, or we round the decimal number to an appropriate number of decimal places. Analyze Which produces a more exact product for multiplying by 0.09, multiplying by 1 11 or by 0.0909?"
"Saxon Math Course 3 Example 1 Express 2 3 as an equivalent decimal and percent. Then express 2 3 as a decimal rounded to the thousandths place. Solution To express 2 3 as a decimal we divide 2 by 3. 3 2.000 0.666... The decimal equivalent to 2 3 is 0.6. To express 2 3 as a percent, we multiply 2 3 by 100%. 3  100%  200%  662 3% To express 2 3 as a decimal rounded to the thousandths place, we write the number with four places and then round back to three places. 0.6 ≈ 0.6666  0.667 Example 2 Express 162 3% as a reduced fraction and as a decimal. Solution A percent is the numerator of a fraction with a denominator of 100. 3%  We perform the division that is indicated. 3  100 3  100  1 One way to convert 162 3% to a decimal is to convert the equivalent fraction 1 to a decimal. 3%  1 6  0.16 The result is reasonable because removing the percent sign shifts the decimal point two places. 3%  0.162 Later in this book we will learn a method for converting decimals with a repetend to fractions and percents."
"Example 3 Arrange these numbers in order from least to greatest. 5, 831 3%, 0.83 Solution To help us compare we will express each number as a decimal rounded to three decimal places. 5  0.800 3% ≈ 0.833 0.83 = 0.830 Now we write the numbers in order. 5, 0.83, 831 3% Example 4 The incumbent received 412 3% of the 1260 votes cast in the town council election. Describe how to estimate the number of votes the incumbent received. Then calculate the exact number of votes. Solution As an approximation we see that the incumbent received somewhat less than half the votes cast, so the number of votes is probably fewer than 600. For a closer estimate we could find 40% of 1260. Since 10% of 1260 is 126, and since 40% is 4 × 10%, we could multiply 4 × 125 to find that the total number of votes should be a little more than 500. Since the percent includes a non-terminating fraction we choose to convert the percent to a fraction to perform the calculation. 3%  125 300  5 We translate the problem into an equation using 5 12 in place of the percent. The incumbent’s votes (v) were 412 3% of the 1260 votes. v  5  1260 v = 525 The incumbent received 525 votes. fractions with negative exponents Recall that a negative exponent indicates the reciprocal of the positive power of the base. x−n = 1 xn 3−2 = 1"
"Saxon Math Course 3 Also recall that with fractions we reverse the position of the numerator and the denominator to form the reciprocal. The reciprocal of x y is y x. If the base of a negative exponent is a fraction, we make the exponent positive by replacing the fraction with its reciprocal. a x yb n = a y xb n Example 5 Simplify: a1 3b −2 Solution We replace 1 3 with its reciprocal, 3, and make the exponent positive. Then we apply the positive exponent. a1 3b 2  32  9 Practice Set Convert each fraction to a decimal and a percent. Then write the decimal rounded to the nearest thousandth. a. 1 b. 5 c. 2 Convert each percent to a fraction and a decimal. Then write the decimal rounded to the nearest hundredth. d. 66 2 3% e. 81 3% f. 22 2 9% g. Arrange in order from least to greatest. 16%, 1 6, 0.165 h. The bill for the meal was $24.00. Dario left a tip of 162 3%. How much was the tip? Simplify. i. a1 2b 3 j. a 1 10b 2 k. a3 2b 1 Written Practice Strengthening Concepts 1. (4) For the centerpieces at the party, four stems of flowers were to be placed in every vase. If there were 72 stems, how many vases could be filled? . ( ) 2. (48) Sixty-five percent of the 1600 students wore school colors on school spirit day. How many students did not wear school colors? 3. (3, 4) Duke carried only dimes. Diana carried just nine nickels. Together they had $1.95. How many dimes did Duke carry?"
