"Saxon Math Course 3 * 17. (Inv. 1, Inv. 2) a. What is the length of the longest side of the triangle? (Hint: Tracing grid lines make a right triangle with the same longest sides.) 5 units b. What is the perimeter of the triangle? 5  325 units * 18. (90) The days that Zachary attends soccer practice (S) and music lessons ( M ) are express in set notation below. S = (M, W, F) M = (T, W) a. Find S ∩ M (The days Zachary attends both soccer practice and music lessons.) {W} b. Find S ∪ M (The days Zachary attends either soccer practice or music lessons or both.) {M, T, W, F} 19. (64, 72) Under standard conditions one kilogram of water occupies 1000 cm3. Use unit multipliers to convert 1000 cm3 to cubic inches. (Either use a calculator to find the volume to the nearest cubic inch or leave the result undivided.) 1000 cm3 ∙ 1 in. 2.54 cm  1 in. 2.54 cm ∙ 1 in. 2.54 cm  (2.54)3 in.3  61 in.3 20. (21) a. Factor: 4 x 2 + 4 x b. Expand: −( x − 3) 4x( x + 1) −x + 3 21. (63) Write 5 11 a as a percent, b as a decimal, and c as a decimal rounded to the nearest thousandth. a. 45 5 11%, b. 0.45 c. 0.455 Solve. 22. (25, 44) 1.2 1.6  9 x x = 12 23. (23, 78) 6 x  1 2 x  1 3 x = 1 24. (41) 0.1 + 0.001 x = 1.01 x = 910 25. (Inv. 2) Study this tile pattern and describe how it illustrates the Pythagorean Theorem. Support your description with an illustration. Sample: The Pythagorean Theorem states that the sum of the squares of the legs of a right triangle equals the square of the hypotenuse. This theorem is illustrated by this picture. The tile pattern repeats this picture of the Pythagorean Theorem."
"L E S S O N Areas of Rectangles with Variable Dimensions Products of Binomials Power Up Building Power facts Fact Power Up S mental math a. Algebra: Solve: 1 2 x = 20 b. Number Sense: What digit is in the one’s place in the product 97 × 97 c. Powers/Roots: m4 m2 d. Probability: Three dozen blocks were in the bag, of which four were red. What is the probability that a block removed at random will not be red? e. Ratio: In an old town, 50 of the 70 residents were miners. What was the ratio of miners to non-miners? f. Select a Method: To find the approximate height of a tall tree, what method would you probably use? A Climb the tree and measure directly. B Use similar figures and a proportion. C Measure the circumference and divide by π. g. Geometry: If two angles are complementary, the sum of their measures is 90°. If ∠C and ∠D are complementary, and m∠C = 60°, find m∠D. h. Calculation: − 1 − 2, + 4, × 5000, ÷ 10, ÷ 10 problem solving A polygon with 3 sides has interior angles with a sum of 180°. A polygon with 4 sides has interior angles with a sum of 360°. A polygon with 5 sides has interior angles with a sum of 540°. If the sum of the interior angles of a polygon is 1800°, how many sides does it have? New Concepts Increasing Knowledge areas of rectangles with variable dimensions Suppose the floor of a square closet with sides measuring 3 ft 6 in. will be covered with one-foot square tiles. We can sketch a plan to show a way the tiles can be arranged and use the sketch to help us find the area of the floor."
"Saxon Math Course 3 ␀FT ␀IN ␀FT ␀IN We see one part of the area is covered with full tiles, two parts are covered with half tiles, and one part is covered with a quarter tile. We count the tiles in each part. 9 full tiles + 3 half tiles + 3 half tiles + 1 quarter tile We can combine the two groups of half tiles. 9 full tiles + 6 half tiles + 1 quarter tile Six half tiles equal three full tiles. We add to find that our sketch shows 12 full tiles and one quarter tile, meaning the area of the floor is 12 1 4 ft. Sketching can also help us visualize the areas of rectangles with dimensions expressed as variables. Example 1 Suppose a rectangular rug measures 21 2 ft by 4 ft. We can represent its area by writing: a2  1 2b a4  1 4b a. Sketch the rectangle on a grid to depict the product. b. What is the total area of the rug? Solution a.       The rectangle is (4  1 4) ft long and (2  1 2) ft wide. The area of each rectangular portion is represented by a different pair of factors from the expression (2  1 2) (4  1 4). b. We multiply each term in one set of parentheses by each term in the other set of parentheses to find the total area. ␀␀␀FT   ␀␀␀FT  "
"Step: Justification: Area = (2  4)  a2  1 4b  a1 2  4b  a1 2  1 4b Area of four regions = 8 + 1 2 + 2 + 1 Multiplied = 10 5 Added As we see in the diagram, the area of the rug is 10 5 8 ft2. Example 2 A rectangle is x + 3 units long and x + 2 units wide. What is the area of the rectangle? Solution This rectangle has side lengths expressed with binomials. We sketch the rectangle and divide the length and width into two parts, representing the two terms of each binomial. This divides the area of the rectangle into four smaller rectangular parts. We find the area of each part. Step: Justification: Area = x2 + 3x + 2x + 6 Added areas of parts Area = x2 + 5x + 6 Combined 3x and 2x products of binomials We can find the area of the rectangle in example 2 by multiplying the binomials. In this part of the lesson we will practice techniques for multiplying binomials. The product of two binomials has four terms, some of which may be like terms. Each term of one binomial is multiplied by each term of the other binomial. We will use an arithmetic model to show the multiplication of two binomials. Breaking out the partial products of the problem on the left, we show that multiplying 43 × 42 is equivalent to multiplying (40 + 3) × (40 + 2). × 42 = = = (40 + 3)2 = = (40 + 3)40 = (40 + 3) × (40 + 2) 80 + 6 1600 + 120 1600 + 200 + 6 = 1806 To find the first partial product on the right, we multiply (40 + 3) by 2 (the “ones place” of the bottom factor) and record the result. To find the second partial product on the left, we multiply (40 + 3) by 40 (the “tens place” of the bottom factor) and record the result. We add all the products to find the total product. We will use this method in example 3. X␀ ␀ X␀ ␀ X X  X  X  X"
"Saxon Math Course 3 Example 3 Expand: ( x + 3) ( x + 2) Solution First we will use an arithmetic model to find the product. ( x + 3) ( x + 2) 2x + 6 x2 + 3x x2 + 5x + 6 Connect Compare the results of this multiplication to the solution to example 2. We must pay attention to the signs when multiplying binomials. Multiplying binomials involves multiplying terms. Every term has a sign. Like signs result in a positive product. Unlike signs result in a negative product. Refer to The acronym FOIL can help us remember the four multiplications that occur when multiplying two binomials. product of two binomials = products of F irst + O utside + I nside + L ast Example 4 Expand: ( x − 3) ( x − 4) Solution Thinking Skill Connect Does reversing the order of the binomials change the product? We can multiply using the algebraic method (and its acronym, FOIL). First we multiply both terms in the second binomial by x. Then we multiply both terms by −3. Step: Justification: ( x − 3) ( x − 4) Given expression X␀Ľ␀ X␀Ľ␀     Applied FOIL x2 − 4x − 3x + 12 Multiplied x2 − 7x + 12 Simplified Practice Set Refer to this rectangle to answer problems a and b. a. Analyze What is the area of the rectangle? (Make a sketch and check by multiplying.) b. Justify What is the area of a square with a side length x + 4? List and explain each step you used to find the answer. X␀à␀ X␀à␀"
"c. Find the product: ( x + 2) ( x + 5). Depict the product with a rectangle. Expand. d. ( x + 1) ( x + 3) e. ( x + 4) ( x + 7) f. ( x + 3)2 g. ( x + 10)2 h. ( x + 8) ( x − 3) i. ( x − 5) ( x + 2) j. ( x + 2) ( x − 2) k. (20 + 2)(20 − 2) Written Practice Strengthening Concepts 1. (67) The old fee of $12 was increased by 175%. What is the new fee? * 2. (87) Analyze Joseph’s workshop is 12 feet by 7 feet. If the drawing of the workshop has a scale of 1 inch = 2 feet, what are the dimensions of the drawing? * 3. (67) Three siblings buy a soccer goal for $29.99 plus 6% tax. Which expression shows the total paid if they split the cost evenly? A ($29.99 × 0.06) ÷ 3 B ($29.99 + 0.06) ÷ 3 C ($29.99 × 1.06) ÷ 3 D ($29.99 + 1.06) ÷ 3 * 4. (1, 16) Model On a number line graph all the real numbers greater than negative 2 that are also less than or equal to 5. * 5. (11, 81) What central angle is formed by the hands of a clock at 4:00? The sector of the arc between the hands at 4:00 is what percent of a full circle? * 6. (90) Analyze The set of the first five counting numbers is {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}. The set of the first five even counting numbers is {2, 4, 6, 8, 10}. a. What is the intersection of the two sets? b. What is the union of the two sets? For problems 7 and 8, write an expression representing the area of each rectangle. 7. (92) X␀ ␀ X␀ ␀ 8. (62) X␀ ␀ X␀Ľ␀ 9. (Inv. 1, Inv. 2) The vertices of a rectangle are at (1, −3), (4, 0), (0, 4), and (−3, 1). Sketch the rectangle and find the length and width of the rectangle. Use the information for problems 10 and 11. 10. (78) What is the area of the rectangle in problem 9? 11. (78, Inv. 2) What is the length of a diagonal of the rectangle?"
"Saxon Math Course 3 12. (80) Write a variable expression for the perimeter of the square with side 2x + 1. * 13. (20, 40) Evaluate A triangle with a base and height of 12 in. is enclosed in a circle which has a diameter of 20 in. a. Visually estimate the percent of the area of the circle occupied by the triangle. b. Find the area of the triangle and the area of the circle. (Use 3.14 for π.) c. Calculate to the nearest percent the portion of the circle occupied by the triangle. 14. (20) Which of the following combinations of lengths cannot construct a triangle? A 2, 3, 4 B 2, 3, 5 C 3, 4, 5 D 3, 4, 6 15. (Inv. 2) Can a right triangle have the side lengths shown? Justify your answer. 16. (72) If the foundation of a new house requires 240 cubic feet of concrete, then how many cubic yards of concrete should be ordered? 17. (75) Find the perimeter and area of the trapezoid. 18. (12) One of the 25 students was absent. Write 1 25 as a a percent and b a decimal. Solve. 19. (25, 44) 2.4 1.8  x 20. (25, 36) 0.05 + 0.01x = 0.4 21. (22, 38) 3  3 4 x  5 22. (50) 3(x + 2) = 2x + 15 23. (42) Find the volume of each prism. The two rectangular prisms are similar figures. Units are in inches. Refer to these figures for problems 24–25.             ␀M ␀M ␀M ␀M ␀M  "
"* 24. (91) a. Analyze What is the scale factor from the smaller to larger prism? b. What is the ratio of the area of one face of the larger prism to the area of the corresponding face of the smaller prism? c. What is the ratio of the volume of the larger prism to the volume of the smaller prism? 25. (Inv. 4, 55) Sketch and label a net of the smaller prism. Early Finishers Real-World Application Rita and Saul are building their first house on a city lot. To provide a proper foundation or their yard, they want to deposit fertilizer-rich topsoil 2-feet deep over their entire yard. Their front yard is rectangular and measures 200 feet by 125 feet. a. What is the area of Rita and Saul’s front yard? How much topsoil do they need (volume)? b. If topsoil sells for $2.95 per cubic yard, about how much should Rita and Saul budget to spend on topsoil?"
"L E S S O N Saxon Math Course 3 Equations with Exponents Power Up Building Power facts Power Up S mental math a. Estimation: $52.80 − $33.05 b. Fractional Parts: 2 9 of 81 c. Percent: 0% more than $30 d. Proportion: x 15  9 e. Scientific Notation: Compare 7.3 × 10−4 0.00073 f. Statistics: Find the mode of this data: 11, 11, 17, 16, 15 g. Measurement: The odometer read 58,254.7 miles at the beginning of the trip. At the end of the trip it read 60,355.9 miles. How long was the trip? h. Calculation: 50 + 13, ÷ 3, ÷ 3, × 7, 2 , × 9 problem solving The original price was $100. For a sale, an employee marked the item down 20%. After the sale, the employee marked the item up 20% from its sale price. What is its current price? New Concept Increasing Knowledge An equation containing a variable with an exponent of 2 (but no greater exponents) is called a quadratic equation. The following is a quadratic equation: x 2 = 25 Both x = 5 and x = −5 are solutions of the equation above, because 52 is 25 and (−5)2 is 25. Every quadratic equation has up to two real solutions. When the solutions are opposites, as in the equation above, we can write them as ±5, which is read “plus or minus five”. Formulate Write a quadratic equation with a solution of x = ±4. Example 1 Solve: 2 x 2 + 7 = 25"
"Solution Math Language Recall that inverse operations are operations that “undo” each other. For example, multiplication is the inverse operation of division. We isolate the x by applying inverse operations. The inverse operation of squaring is finding the square root. Step: Justification: 2x2 + 7= 25 Given equation 2 x 2 = 18 Subtracted 7 from both sides x 2 = 9 Divided both sides by 2 x = ±3 Found square roots of 9 Check by testing both solutions in the original equation. Check x = 3 Justification Check x = −3 2(3)2 + 7 = 25 Substituted 2(−3)2 + 7 = 25 2(9) + 7 = 25 Simplified 2(9) + 7 = 25 25 = 25 (true) Simplified 25 = 25 (true) There are two solutions of this equation because every positive number has two square roots. If x 2 = 9, then x = ±3. Example 2 Solve: 2 x 2 = 16 Solution Step: Justification: 2 x 2 = 16 Given x 2 = 8 Divided both sides by 2 x = ± 28 Found square roots of 8 x = ± 222 Simplified 28 Note that the radical sign indicates only the positive square root, also called the principal square root. 29  3 In Examples 1 and 2 we used ± to indicate both the positive and negative solutions. Example 3 The two rectangles are similar. Find x by solving this proportion. Solve: 9 x  x ␀CM X X ␀CM"
"Saxon Math Course 3 Solution Solve for x. Step: Justification: x  x Given equation x 2 = 9 ∙ 16 Cross multiplied x 2 = 144 Multiplied 9 and 16 x = ±12 Found the square roots of 144 Both 12 and −12 are solutions of the proportion. Check x = 12 Justification Check x = −12 12  12 Substituted 12  12 4  3 Simplified 3 4  3 For applications of quadratic equations, often only one of the solutions will make sense. We must consider physical reality when reporting solutions. In this situation, only +12 applies because lengths are positive. The dimension is 12 cm. Example 4 Jaime is making a mosaic using 100 one-inch square tiles. If the shape of his mosaic is to be a square, about how long should each side be? Solution Since the area of Jaime’s mosaic will be 100 in.2, we can use the area formula to solve for the length of each side. Step: Justification: A = s 2 Formula for area of a square 100 in.2 = s 2 Substituted 100 in.2 for A ±10 in. = s Found square roots of 100 in.2 Although we find two solutions of the equation, only the principal square root makes sense in this situation—a side length must be positive. Jamie should make his mosaic 10 in. on each side. Discuss Discuss Why is it a good idea to reread the problem after solving for x? Practice Set Evaluate Solve and check both solutions to each quadratic equation. a. 2 x 2 − 3 = 29 b. 5 x 2 + 6 = 16 c. −7 x 2 + 8 = −13 d. 8 = 4 w 2 − 24 e. 4 x  x f. x 3  4 x g. Yoli arranges 121 square tiles into one larger square. How many tiles are along each edge of the larger square?"
