"L E S S O N Graphing Pairs of Inequalities on a Number Line Power Up Building Power facts Power Up S mental math a. Algebra: Solve: x 3  6 b. Estimation: $230 − $58.99 c. Number Sense: What digit is in the ones place in the product 183 × 183? d. Powers/Roots: m5 m5 e. Rate: Six classes per day is how many classes per 5-day week? f. Statistics: What is the mode, median, and range of the number of days in the 12 months of a common year? g. Geometry: Angle X and ∠Z are complementary. If m ∠X = 80º, find m ∠Z. h. Calculation: 63 ÷ 3, ÷ 7, × 33, + 3, × 2, + 1 problem solving Can one item be removed from each side of the scale and have it remain balanced? If so, which items can be removed? If not, why? New Concept Increasing Knowledge We have graphed inequalities on a number line. In some situations, we consider pairs of inequalities. For example, suppose we know that the heights of professional male basketball players range from 5′5″ (65 in.) to 7′6″ (90 in.). This can be expressed on a number line and with an inequality expression.      ␀ǔ␀H␀ǔ␀    The inequality expression can be read “h is greater than or equal to 65 and less than or equal to 90.” The expression can be written: h ≥ 65 and h ≤ 90 M M M    "
"Saxon Math Course 3 Notice the graph of the inequality contains only the points that are both greater than or equal to 65 and less than or equal to 90. The graph is the intersection (overlap) of the graphs of h ≥ 65 and h ≤ 90.      H␀␀         H␀␀         ␀␀H␀␀    Explain What do the closed circles at 65 and 90 indicate? Example 1 Use a number-line graph and an inequality expression to describe the statement: “The length of one side (s) of a triangle is greater than 2 and less than 8.” Solution The side length cannot equal 2 or 8, so we use open circles.            Since s > 2 and s < 8, we write: 2  s  8 Example 2 Graph the solution set of the inequality −1  x  5. Solution We graph the numbers greater than or equal to −1 and less than 5. Ľ  Ľ␀␀X␀ ␀ Predict How would the graph look if the statement were −1 < x < 5? Suppose school officials cancel outdoor physical education classes when the outside temperature is below 40ºF or above 100ºF. If t represents the outside temperature, this rule can be expressed: t < 40 or t > 100 Example 3 Graph this pair of inequalities: t  40 or t  100"
"Solution We use the word “or” to indicate that t must meet one or the other condition, not both. Therefore, the graph is the union (or combination) of the graphs of each inequality.          Thinking Skill Analyze Can we graph the intersection of the solutions of x < 1 and x > 2? Why or why not? To summarize, when we graph a pair of solutions with an “and” statement we graph the intersection. Ľ Ľ    X␀␀Ľ␀AND␀X␀␀ Ľ␀␀X␀␀   When we graph a pair of solution with an “or” statement, we graph the union. Ľ    X␀␀Ľ␀OR␀X␀␀  Discuss How is an intersection different from a union? Practice Set Graph these inequalities on a number line. a. −3 < x < 3 b. x ≤ −3 or x ≥ 3 c. 5 < x ≤ 10 d. x < 0 or x ≥ 5 e. Represent A college will cancel a lab class if less than 12 students enroll. No more than 30 students can enroll in one lab class. Write an inequality that shows the numbers of students (s) that could be in a lab class and illustrate this inequality on a number line. Written Practice Strengthening Concepts 1. (48) About 30,000 prospectors made it to Dawson City during the Klondike Gold Rush. If this total was about 30% of those participating in the Gold Rush, about how many of the participants did not make it to Dawson City? * 2. (67) Estimate An item that regularly sold for $199 was marked down to $139. Estimate the percent discount. 3. (87) The scale of a model car is 1 in. = 1.5 feet. If the model is 8 inches long, how long is the actual car? * 4. (32) Analyze If you roll two number cubes at the same time, what is the probability that both number cubes will show odd numbers? 5. (9, Inv. 4) Square ABCD has vertices A (0, 2), B (2, 0), C (0, −2), D (−2, 0). a. Sketch ABCD. b. A rotation of how many degrees shows that ABCD has rotational symmetry?"
