"L E S S O N Saxon Math Course 3 Recursive Rules for Sequences Power Up Building Power facts Power Up T mental math a. Algebra: Solve: y + 7 = 10 b. Estimation: Estimate the product in hours: 66 minutes × 7 c. Fractional Parts: 6 7 of 70 d. Percent: 60% more than $10 e. Rate: Two thousand calories per day is how many calories per week? f. Geometry: A square pyramid barely fits into a cube-shaped box. If each edge of the box is 3 inches, what is the volume of the pyramid? g. Measurement: Find the unknown mass. h. Calculation: 10 − 12, × 30, + 70, − 8, × 18 problem solving When a top makes one revolution, it rotates 360º. If a top spins at a rate of 300 revolutions per minute, how many degrees per second is that? New Concept Increasing Knowledge Recall that a sequence is an ordered list of numbers that follow a certain pattern or rule. {3, 6, 9, 12, …} Also recall that we distinguish between the position of the term (such as 1st, 2nd, 3rd) and the value of a term (such as 3, 6, 9). Term Position (n) … Term Value (a) … We have written and used formulas that show how to find the value of a term if we know its position. The following formula will generate any term of the sequence above. The notation an refers to the term value (a) at position n. The subscripts only indicate position; they are not involved in any calculations. an = 3n     "
"In place of n we substitute the position of the term we wish to find. Thus, to find the 7th term we substitute 7 for n in the formula. a7 = 3(7) = 21 The a7 in the calculations above refers to the value of the term in the 7th position of the sequence. The value of the term in the 7th position of the sequence is 21. We can also write formulas that show how a term in a sequence relates to a preceding term or terms. Thinking Skill Infer The subscripts in the formulas in this lesson refer to position. The subscript n−1 refers to the term preceding the nth term. What would the subscript of the term following the nth term be? In the previous sequence, the value of a term is 3 more than the preceding term. We may write the rule this way: an = an−1 + 3 In this formula an is the nth term and an−1 is the term just before it. So if we know any term in this sequence (an−1), then we can find the next term (an) by adding 3 to that term. This kind of formula for a sequence is called a recursive formula. When we write a recursive formula, we also indicate the first term (a1) of the sequence. In this case the first term is 3. a1 = 3 an = an−1 + 3 • We use the first term to find the second term, the second term to find the third term, and so on. Example 1 Write a recursive formula for the following sequence: {2, 4, 8, 16, 32, …} Solution The first term is 2. Each term that follows is twice the preceding term.  ␀␀ ␀␀ ␀␀ ␀␀ ␀ ␀ X X X X X X Therefore, we find the nth term (an) by multiplying the preceding term (an−1) by 2. an = 2an−1 Since the first term is 2, we can express the recursive formula this way. • a1 = 2 an = 2an−1 Example 2 This formula shows how to find any term of a sequence. Use the formula to find the first four terms of the sequence. an = 1 + 2n Then write a recursive formula for this sequence."
"Saxon Math Course 3 Solution To find the first four terms we replace n with 1, then 2, then 3, then 4, and simplify. n = 1 a1 = 1 + 2(1) = 3 n = 2 a2 = 1 + 2(2) = 5 n = 3 a3 = 1 + 2(3) = 7 n = 4 a4 = 1 + 2(4) = 9 The first four terms are 3, 5, 7, 9. We see that the first term, a1, is 3. We also see that each term is 2 greater (+2) than the preceding term. So the recursive formula is: a1 = 3 • an = an−1 + 2 Example 3 A recursive formula for a sequence is a1 = 5 • an = 3 an−1 Find the second and third terms. Solution The recursive formula gives the first term. We can use the first term and the formula to find the second term. The formula shows that each term is 3 times the preceding term. Since 3 ∙ 5 = 15, the second term is 15 and the third term is 45. Predict One term in this sequence is 405. What is the term following 405? Practice Set a. Write a recursive formula for the following sequence: 1, 4, 16, 64, . . . b. The terms of the following sequence are generated with the formula an = 5n – 2. Write a recursive formula for this sequence: 3, 8, 13, 18, . . . c. One of the terms in the following sequence is 729. Write a recursive formula for the sequence and find the term that follows 729. 1, 3, 9, 27, . . . d. Which formula below generates the terms of the following sequence? 2, 3, 5, 9, 17, 33 . . . A •a1 = 2 an = 2an−1 – 1 B an = 2n – 1 C •a1 = 2 an = an−1 + 1"
