"L E S S O N Saxon Math Course 3 Converting Repeating Decimals to Fractions Power Up Building Power facts Power Up V mental math a. Algebra: Solve: 1 2 (50 n ) = 125 b. Number Sense: A perfect square has a 9 in the ones place. Its square root has a or a in the ones place. c. Powers/Roots: ( r 2)4 d. Probability: A random number generator gives a random number from 1 to 20. Rob designs a game where he wants the probability of a special event to be 25%. He wants special events to happen when the random number generator gives low numbers. What numbers should be assigned special events? e. Ratio: In the game of capture the flag, there were 32 participants. If 12 players were your opponents, what was the ratio of your opponents to your teammates? f. Statistics: The photographer lined up 21 students in order of height. The height of the 11th student in line represents the A mean. B median. C mode. D range. g. Geometry: A right triangle has one angle that measures 90°. What is the sum of the other two angles? h. Calculation: 21 2 × 2, × 2, × 2, × 2, × 2, × 2 problem solving Use the given information to answer a and b. a. Two brothers are 5 years apart, and the sum of their ages is 41. What are the ages of the brothers? b. A girl is 3 times the age of her younger sister, and the sum of their ages is 20. What are the ages of the sisters? New Concept Increasing Knowledge Recall from Lesson 30 that some fractions convert to repeating decimals. 11  11 .27272  3.00000"
"Math Language Recall that the repetend is the part of a repeating decimal that repeats without end. One way to express a repeating decimal is by writing a bar over the repetend. 11  0.27 To convert a repeating decimal to a fraction we write three equations using algebra to remove the repeating part of the decimal. 1. To write the first equation we choose a variable, like f (for fraction), and make it equal to the decimal. f  0.27 2. To make the second equation we first count the numbers of digits that repeat. Then we multiply both sides of the first equation by a power of 10 using the number of repeating digits as the exponent. For example, the decimal 0.27 has two digits that repeat (0.272727...), so we multiply by 102, or 100. 100f = 100(0.27) Multiplied both sides of first equation by 100 100f  27.27 Simplified Notice that the decimal in this second equation has the same repetend as the decimal in the first equation. 3. To make the third equation, we subtract the first equation from the second equation. Second equation 100f = 27.27 − First equation f = 0.27 Third equation 99f = 27.0 Since the repetends are identical, subtracting 0.27 from 27.27 results in a third equation without a repetend. We solve the third equation and reduce to find the equivalent fraction. 99f = 27 f  27 99  3 Example 1 Convert 0.16 to a fraction. Solution We write three equations. This time we show an alternate way to indicate a repetend, using three dots (called an ellipsis) to show in this case that the pattern of repetition continues. First equation f = 0.16666... One digit repeats (0.1666...) so we multiply both sides by 10, which shifts the decimal point one place. Second equation 10 f = 1.6666..."
"Saxon Math Course 3 Now we make a third equation by subtracting the first from the second. Second equation 10f = 1.6666. . . − First equation f = 0.1666. . . Third equation 9f = 1.5 The third equation is 9 f = 1.5. We solve the equation. 9 f = 1.5 f  1.5 Since the fraction has a decimal, we multiply the fraction by 10 10 to shift the decimal point one place and reduce the fraction. 1.5 9  10 10  15 90  1 Example 2 The theoretical probability of rolling 12 with two number cubes is 0.027. About how many times would you expect to roll 12 in 180 rolls? Solution We have a choice of rounding 0.027 or converting to an equivalent fraction. Since rounding introduces small errors we choose to convert to a fraction. One digit repeats so we multiply by 10. f  0.027 10f  0.277 Now we subtract the first equation from the second equation and reduce. 10f  0.277 − f = 0.027 9 f = 0.25 f  0.25 To clear the decimal we multiply by 100 100, forming an equivalent fraction without decimals. We reduce this fraction to find the answer. 0.25  100 100  25 900  1 The decimal probability 0.027 is equivalent to the fraction 1 36. This means we would expect 12 as the outcome 1 36 of the times we roll a pair of number cubes. We find 1 36 of 180. 36  180  180 36  5 In 180 rolls we would expect to roll 12 five times."
