"24. (7) Find the mean and median of 10.4, 10.6, 10.8, 10.0 and 9.8. Round each to one decimal place. 25. (91) Suppose you have enough money to buy either one 12-inch pizza or two 8-inch pizzas. Which choice gives you more pizza? Explain your answer. Early Finishers Real-World Application The city council funded a new spherical water tank that is 200 feet wide to top the town’s water tower. Before putting it to use, the city will paint its surface and fill the tank to capacity. Determine the approximate area to be painted and volume of the spherical tank. (Use 3.14 for π.)"
"L E S S O N Saxon Math Course 3 Calculating Area as a Sweep Power Up Building Power facts Power Up W mental math a. Estimation: 29 × 68 b. Number Sense: Can a perfect square have a 2 in the ones place? c. Powers/Roots: (x3)3 x2 d. Proportion: 3 6  2 x e. Scientific Notation: Compare 320 3.2 × 10 f. Statistics: Which measure of central tendency could be used to find the most common size of shirt sold? g. Geometry: Two angles in a triangle measure 18° and 52°. Find the measure of the third angle. h. Calculation: 10 − 8, + 2, × 9, + 4, × 2, + 1 problem solving The buckets on each side of the pulley contain the same total mass. Is it possible to remove 2 blocks from each side and have the total masses remain equal? If so, which 2 from each side can be removed? New Concept Increasing Knowledge Imagine using a push broom to clean a dirty floor or sidewalk. As you push the broom it sweeps an area. The area the broom sweeps is equal to the width of the broom times the distance the broom is pushed. !REA DISTANCE PUSHED WIDTH OF BROOM    X  X X "
"Now imagine sweeping an area with one side of the broom held in place. The broom sweeps a circular area. The area equals the width of the broom times the average (mean) distance the broom is pushed. We will apply this concept of sweeping to calculate some areas and surface areas. We start with a circle, then we calculate the lateral surface area of a cylinder and a cone. Look at the minute hand of a watch or clock. In one hour the minute hand sweeps all the way around the circular face of the clock. Every point inside the circle the length of the minute hand is swept across by that hand. Notice that the minute hand represents the radius of the circular face of the clock. Example 1 As radius CA turns, it sweeps the area of a circle. a. How wide is “broom CA” (radius)? b. How far does point A move in one full turn? c. How far does point C move in one full turn? d. What is the average distance the points from A to C move during one full turn? e. The area of the circle is the product of the length of “broom CA” and the average distance the points of the broom move. What is the area? Solution a. The length of “broom CA” is equal to the radius, 5 cm. b. Point A moves a distance equal to the circumference, 10𝛑 cm. c. Point C moves 0 cm. (It does not move.) d. The average (mean) distance moved by a point on the radius is the average of 10π cm and 0 cm, which is 5𝛑 cm. Thinking Skill Verify Use the formula for the area of a circle to verify that the area calculated as a sweep is correct. e. The product of the radius and its average distance moved is 5 cm ∙ 5π cm = 25π cm2. The area is 25𝛑 cm2. # xÊV !"
"Saxon Math Course 3 Recall that the lateral surface area of a cylinder is represented by the label of a can. We can calculate the lateral surface area of a cylinder as a sweep. We show two ways. • Method 1: Sweep with the circumference Imagine the upper rim of a can is a circular broom. As it slides down the can it sweeps the entire lateral surface of the can. The length of the broom is the circumference of the can. The distance the broom moves is the height of the can. • Method 2: Sweep with the height. Imagine segment AB sweeping around the can. The length of the “broom” is the height of the can. The distance it moves is the circumference of the circle. With both methods we find the lateral surface area by multiplying the circumference of the can and the height of the can. lateral surface area of cylinder = circumference × height S = 2π r h or S = π dh Example 2 Calculate the lateral surface area of the cone. The diameter of the base is 2 in., and the slant height is 4 in. Solution We can imagine segment AB as a broom that sweeps once around the lateral surface of the cone. Point B travels the circumference of the base. Point does not move (travels 0 in.). The average distance the points along AB travel is the average (mean) of 0 and the circumference of the base. Thus, the lateral surface area can be found using this equation: surface area = length of AB × 0  circumference  4 in.  0  2p in. = 4 in. × π in. = 4 𝛑 in.2 ! "" ␀IN !""␀â␀␀IN "" ␀CM ␀CM !"
"We can use similar calculations to develop a formula for the lateral surface area of a cone. lateral surface area = circumference × slant height ( l ) of cone S  2 pr  l S = π r l lateral surface area = π r l Finally, imagine sweeping an area with a broom that becomes narrower and narrower. The broom sweeps an area the shape of a trapezoid or triangle. The area of the trapezoid or triangle equals the average (mean) width of the broom times the distance it is pushed. Practice Set a. Explain Imagine a broom steadily narrowing from 12 in. to 0 in. as it sweeps 10 in. to form a triangle. Describe how to find the area of the triangle. b. Segment AB is 5 cm long and the diameter of the cylinder is 10 cm long. Describe how to calculate the lateral surface area of the cylinder. Find the lateral surface area expressed in terms of π. L ␀IN ␀IN ! "" ␀CM ␀CM"
"Saxon Math Course 3 c. How long is the slant height of this cone? If the slant height sweeps around the cone, what is the average distance it moves? What is the lateral surface area of the cone? (Use 3.14 for π.) d. Write the formula for the lateral surface area of a cone. Then use the formula to find how many square inches of paper are used to make a paper party hat of these dimensions. (Use 22 7 for π.) Written Practice Strengthening Concepts 1. (48) Seventeen of the twenty chairs were occupied. What percent of the chairs were not occupied? 2. (105) Michael read an average of 14 pages a day for 5 days and 28 pages a day for 2 days. What was the average number of pages Michael read for the seven days? 3. (3, 4) The party cost $300 for the “Big Bounce” plus $4 for each child’s food. If the party costs $416 how many children came? Simplify problems 4–9. 4. (27, 36) (3x3)4 5. (37, 36) (2y4)5 6. (80) (2m − 3x + y) + (2m + 3x − y) 7. (80) (3w − 4x − y) + (3w + 4x − y) 8. (93) a1 3b 9. (93) a 3 2.1b 10. (27, 51) 48wx2y1 32x2y2 * 11. (61) Evaluate The first three terms of the sequence an = 2n + 3 are shown below. 5, 7, 9, … a. What is the 100th term? b. What position in the sequence is 99? 12. (82) Give the x and y intercepts, then graph 4x + 2y = −12 ␀CM ␀CM ␀IN ␀IN"
